hands_on_practices.solution:
We compute the residual for the original system. With $A=\begin{pmatrix} 3  -1 \\ 1  2 \end{pmatrix}$, $b=\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$, and $x_{k}=\begin{pmatrix} 2.1 \\ 1.2 \end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix} \frac{21}{10} \\ \frac{6}{5} \end{pmatrix}$, first evaluate
$$
A x_{k}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
3  -1 \\
1  2
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{21}{10} \\
\frac{6}{5}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
3\cdot\frac{21}{10}-1\cdot\frac{6}{5} \\
1\cdot\frac{21}{10}+2\cdot\frac{6}{5}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{63}{10}-\frac{12}{10} \\
\frac{21}{10}+\frac{24}{10}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{51}{10} \\
\frac{45}{10}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Thus the residual is
$$
r_{k}=b-Ax_{k}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
5 \\
5
\end{pmatrix}
-
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{51}{10} \\
\frac{45}{10}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
-\frac{1}{10} \\
\frac{1}{2}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Its Euclidean norm satisfies
$$
\|r_{k}\|_{2}^{2}=\left(-\frac{1}{10}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{100}+\frac{1}{4}=\frac{26}{100}=\frac{13}{50},
$$
so
$$
\|r_{k}\|_{2}=\sqrt{\frac{13}{50}}.
$$
With tolerance $\epsilon=0.4=\frac{2}{5}$, compare squares:
$$
\|r_{k}\|_{2}^{2}=\frac{13}{50} \quad\text{and}\quad \epsilon^{2}=\left(\frac{2}{5}\right)^{2}=\frac{4}{25}=\frac{8}{50}.
$$
Since $\frac{13}{50}\frac{8}{50}$, it follows that $\|r_{k}\|_{2}\epsilon$, so the stopping criterion is not met for the original system.

For the scaled system with $c=5$, we have $A'=cA$ and $b'=cb$. The residual is
$$
r'_{k}=b'-A'x_{k}=cb-cAx_{k}=c(b-Ax_{k})=c\,r_{k},
$$
hence the norm scales linearly:
$$
\|r'_{k}\|_{2}=|c|\,\|r_{k}\|_{2}=5\sqrt{\frac{13}{50}}.
$$
Because $5\sqrt{\frac{13}{50}}\sqrt{\frac{13}{50}}\frac{2}{5}$, the stopping criterion is also not met for the scaled system. Therefore, the correct choice is that the criterion is not met for either system.
